<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910926-0067</DOCNO><DOCID>910926-0067.</DOCID><HL>   Dean Foods Probes   Possible Bid-Rigging   By Dairy Units</HL><DATE>09/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DF</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><NS>COMMODITIES MARKET (CMD)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   GREEN BAY, Wis. -- Dean Foods Co. said it is investigatingpossible bid-rigging of school milk contracts by its dairiesin several states.   The company's chairman also told shareholders at Dean'sannual meeting that two employees in Texas have been put onleave of absence until the company's involvement in a federalinvestigation has been resolved.</LP><TEXT>   The Justice department is known to be looking into bidcollusion and other illegalities by numerous dairies in atleast 16 states. The investigations, now several years old,already have resulted in 40 criminal cases against 50defendants, corporate fines totaling $18 million and jailterms for 16 individuals.   Dean units already have been involved in cases in Floridaand Texas. In July, Dean and two of its units, Grandy's andBell dairies, paid a total of $750,000 in fines to settle acivil case brought by the Texas attorney general. Stateauthorities had brought a civil case against seven dairiesalleging that they allocated school districts amongthemselves, then inflated milk prices for school mealprograms. Dean paid the fines without admitting guilt.   Last September, the Justice Department named two otherDean units, T.G. Lee Foods of Orlando and McArthur Dairy ofMiami, in a criminal count alleging conspiracy to rig milkbids in Florida. Each company paid the government a $1million fine.   Dean, based in Franklin Park, Ill., is the nation'ssecond-largest dairy.   Howard M. Dean, chairman and chief executive officer ofDean Foods, gave no details of the company's internalinvestigation. He limited his remarks to assuring holdersthat &quot;we do not anticipate that the outcome of theseinvestigations will have a material effect on the company'sfinancial condition. Dean Foods has never condoned this typeof activity.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>